Overview
In Stage 0, you provisioned a Linux server and configured nginx. In Stage 1, you will build and deploy a secure API that interacts with the GitHub API to report its own deployment status. As a DevOps engineer, you must ensure services are not only running but are resource-constrained and secure. The backend is minimal, but the operational requirements are strict.

What You Must Do


Build the API: 
Write an API in any language that requires an `X-Api-Key` header for all requests.

Required Key: HNG-DEVOPS-STAGE-1-SECRET-KEY
Error Handling: Any request without this key or with an incorrect key must return a 401 Unauthorized status with a JSON error message..
{
  "error": "Unauthorized",
  "message": "Invalid or missing X-Api-Key"
}

Endpoints:
GET /: Returns {“message”: “API is running”}`
GET /health: Returns the current CPU and Memory usage of the server.
{
  "cpu_usage": "X%",
  "memory_usage": "X MB"
}

GET /me : Returns a JSON response containing:

Your full name and email (sourced from a .env file).
Your GitHub profile URL.
The name of the current repository.
The status and conclusion of the latest GitHub Actions deployment workflow for this project
{
  "name": "Your Full Name",
  "email": "you@example.com",
  "github_url": "https://github.com/yourusername",
  "repo_name": "your-repo-name",
  "workflow_status": "completed",
  "workflow_conclusion": "success"
}All endpoints must return Content-Type: application/json, an HTTP status code of 200 (on success), and respond within 300ms.

2. Deploy It
Process Management: You must use systemd to manage your application.
Resource Limits: The systemd service must be configured to strictly limit the application to:

CPU: 10%
Memory: 128MB
Security: Deploy using an nginx Reverse Proxy. Use a firewall to ensure the application port is not publicly accessible; only nginx (Port 80/443) should be reachable.

3. Document It
Push your code to a public GitHub repository with a README that includes:

Project description and local setup instructions.
The API endpoints and expected responses.
The live deployment URL.




Evaluation Criteria:

All endpoints must return `Content-Type: application/json`.
All successful requests must return HTTP 200; unauthorized requests must return HTTP 401.
The /me endpoint must successfully pull and display the latest GitHub Actions workflow status for the repo.
The service must be managed by `systemd` with the specified CPU and Memory quotas enforced.
The application port must be firewalled, with traffic served only via Nginx.
All endpoints must respond within 300ms.
The GitHub repository must be public.
ANY exposed secrets (API keys, tokens, or .env files) found in the GitHub repository history will result in deducted narks


